title: Prep Roundup, Oct. 8
text:
VOLLEYBALL 
Tigers sweep CMB 
Gilbert got stronger and stronger as its match wore on versus Collins-Maxwell-Baxter Thursday in Baxter as the Tigers swept the Raiders in three sets. 
Gilbert won by scores of 25-19, 25-16 and 25-9 to improve to 17-7 overall and 5-2 in the Heart of Iowa Conference. CMB fell to 10-8 and 2-4 respectively. 
Bridget Hurley battled through an injury to come up with seven kills for CMB. Mikayla Eslinger added four kills, Jordynn Wesselink had three kills, Sailor Hinegardner finished with eight digs and Toni Spencer chipped in seven digs for the Raiders. 
Spencer also went 10 of 12 serving with two aces. Payge Jurgens was 8 of 10 serving for CMB with one ace. 
Ogden sweeps Royals 
The Ogden volleyball team beat Colo-NESCO, 3-0, on Thursday night. 
Ogden won the opening set, 25-21; the second set, 25-9; and the third set, 25-16. 
Norse win Perry tournament 
The Roland-Story volleyball team won the Perry Tournament on Thursday, winning four matches and dropping just one set all evening. 
The Norse swept Ballard, Saydel and Perry, and topped Woodward-Granger, 2-1. They are now 13-9 this season. 
CROSS COUNTRY 
Little Cyclones go 5th, 10th at Fort Dodge 
The Ames cross country teams competed at the Fort Dodge Invitiational on Thursday. The girls’ team finished 5th out of 17 teams, while the boys finished 10th out of 18. 
The girls were led by Claire Dupuis, who finished fourth with a time of 18:21. Katelyn Moore followed in 21st with a time of 19:44. On the whole, the Little Cyclones scored 154 points; Urbandale won the event with 28. 
Marcus Reecy led the boys’ effort by finishing 27th in 16:50. Lee Grim and Brian Todey followed in 42nd and 43rd with matching times of 16:59. Ames finished with 242 points, while Dowling Catholic won the event with 37. 
Local teams fare well at Jim Klein Invite 
Six local high schools competed at the Jim Klein Invitational in Jewell on Thursday. 
The Gilbert cross country teams took first place in both the boys’ and girls’ competition. The Tigers won with 62 points in the boys race while the girls won with 29. 
The South Hamilton boys’ cross country team finished fifth with 160 points, and Nevada finished in sixth with 172. Colo-NESCO followed behind in seventh, while Roland-Story and Collins-Maxwell-Baxter finished ninth and 12th, respectively. 
The CMB girls’ team finished second behind Gilbert with 75 points. Nevada’s girls team finished sixth while Colo-NESCO, Roland-Story and South Hamilton finished eighth, ninth and 13th.
